claybank@img.net
[Sorry it wasnÂ´t clear. The hantavirus involved is Hantaan virus -- see
ref. (02) above.
Congo-Crimean hemorrhagic fever (CCHF) virus is a nairovirus, not a
hantavirus, & was *not* involved in Samara. But since both cause
hemorrhagic fevers & the symptoms are similar, the population connected the
two outbreaks in their minds.
You are correct; hantaviruses are transmitted by exposure to dusts
contaminated with infective urine or feces, whereas CCHF virus is
transmitted by ticks, which would not be active in the cold season. -
Mod.JW
